# backgroundSubtraction

**Confocal Image Data Analysis with Python**
**Tanner Fink (fink.240@osu.edu)**



**What kind of data can I analyze?**

Originally intended for processing raw data from ImageJ measurements (typically from a batch processing macro)â€”currently the program can handle any number of channels and look at up to 2 channels at a time.

The program makes a few assumptions about the nature of your input file.  The file **must** be an excel xlsx. Format,have a 1-row header above the data, a label on the leftmost part of each row after the header, and the rightmost column in a row contain the background measurement.  An example of anonymized data is shown below.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)







**How do I run an analysis?**

Run the program by launching &quot;backSubWindow.py&quot;.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

In this example, the original confocal image had two channels, (Label1 = Channel1, Label2= Channel2, etc..).  Suppose one wanted to background subtract just the first channel, the program may look something like this:

**Results**

Now simply hit &quot;Run Analysis&quot; and you&#39;re done!  The file will export in the same directory the program is run from, and will be named &quot;background\_subtracted.xlsx&quot; by default.  An example of results are indicated below to the right, and a manual validation is included on the left for comparison.
